ive been a mets fan my whole life. there's a closet in oregon full of childhood pictures. im wearin a mets hat in about half of em my white locks sticking awkwardly out the sides of my cap.

in there, theres also a picture of me with my little brother @dirtydoggy sittin on my lap wearin my mets hat which was way too big for his lil head. we're hoverin over a newspaper and im trying to explain how to read baseball box scores. that was probably one of the first times i tried to convince him to like baseball. but he wasnt a big sports fan growin up. he always wanted to skate and take pictures. but when i moved to new york, somethin changed. we started going to mets games together. he bought a mets hat. and it's something we both get excited about.

bein a mets fan is never easy. i didnt know that when i was 6, but ive learned it my whole life. a lot of people have picked the yankees because theyve been really good the last 20 years or so and the mets have mostly been sad. but while the yankees are the handsome face, the mets are the soul baby! you might be tempted to pick the yankees at the dance because damn look how good they look in a suit, but youll soon realize theyre pretty boring and dont have anything interesting to say. the mets. the mets are the one you'll have fun bein with.

your favorite sports team is like family. you cant pick it. it picks you. and then youre stuck with em the rest of your life. you take em for granted sometimes you get mad at em. but every once in a while, they do somethin really special. somethin that surprises you and realize, wow it‚Äôs pretty great that theyre around.

this season was one of those moments both for the mets and my lil bro. nobody expected the mets to be very good this year but they are. theyre fun and exciting and do silly things like make @wefollowlucasduda. and it's pretty awesome how much my lil bro's embraced them and that we're both freaking out right now hopin for the same thing tonight.

win or lose, this was the best season i've ever had as a sports fan. this picture is us. he's jerry seinfeld and i'm jon stewart because i'm cooler and he gets upset about everything.

so... lets go mets!!

I received this in the mail the other day and tore through it rather quickly- this volume is an odd little book, and I mean this entirely as a compliment. Matt Johnson is an RVA resident who has been a mathematician, played in punk bands, worked at the Pentagon, written and edited books on mathematics, is a motorcycle freak, & tends to think deeply on the state of our nation & what it is to be an American, often writing from the position of a governmental office worker, a world that fascinates me at times but that I know nothing about- that is what this book is, a collection of 50 short stories/essays dealing with the problems our country faces, the highly-varied nature of American identity, odd characters he's met on road trips & inspirational people from history (including some pretty unlikely ones, not all American), & more than a bit of soul searching on his own part to find  personal fulfillment while serving the greater good. The author doesn't shy away from discussing where things have gone wrong in our country, but doesn't pontificate from that tired old bipartisan windbag position you hear so much of from today's politicians- the dude seems to honestly want to help make things better, not just complain & blame others. I learned a few interesting history lessons (something I am always grateful for) & even got a few laughs in (the story "You Can't Get a Girlfriend Listening to the Smiths on Repeat" was hilariously awkward). At just over 100 pages, the book is well-written, quite slim, but beautifully designed- it's a pleasure to read & hold- I am a big fan of good book design, & you can tell Johnson really took his time with this one. It's a beautiful object in a tactile sense. "American Hearts" is inspirational, but not in that mawkish sickly-sweet Hallmark card way, so I hereby recommend it. You can order "American Hearts" by Matt Johnson from Amazon.com (not sure if it's available in bookstores in RVA, but you could check). Thanks for the book, Matt! #isupportlocalauthors #americanhearts #turnoffthetvandexerciseyourmindplease
